Git is an open-source, distributed version control system. It is a command-line tool that tracks changes in source code and other files. While GitHub is a service for Git repositories. It provides a cloud-based platform to store and manage Git projects.
I'm curious about how the tech works, like the tech that runs git and GitHub. 
Vocab: A 
repository is the central storage location for a project, containing all project files, folders, and their complete revision history. 
Cloning refers to creating a local copy of a remote repository on your computer. A  
commit represents a snapshot of the project at a specific point in time. When you make changes to your code and save them
 Pushing involves uploading your local commits from your local repository to the remote repository on GitHub
Branches are independent lines of development within a repository. They allow you to work on new features or bug fixes without affecting the main codebase. 
